##Flight Sharp reduction, the resumption of business charter aircraft, the epidemic of the aviation industry in a hundred states

Illiquid, small airlines will struggle

Chen Liang, Wang Jingyi
Stephen chi-leung | editor

A member of staff guides passengers onto a plane at the Shenyang Taoxian International Airport on February 21,2020. Photo / China News

Chen Liang, Wang Jingyi

Stephen chi-leung | editor

A member of staff guides passengers onto a plane at the Shenyang Taoxian International Airport on February 21,2020. Photo / China News

At one time, there was a long line of tourists around 5 am on a weekday, and the Shanghai Hongqiao International Airport of the epidemic in the COVID-19("new coronavirus") was unusually quiet.

Business travelers between Beijing and Shanghai are also hard to find. At noon on February 26, the counter at Hongqiao Airport Island B was closed and the open counter at island a was deserted. During the epidemic took the plane of High Peng to "finance and Economics" reporter Sigh, Pudong Airport so big Eastern Airlines Lounge, only 5 people, simply can lie.

The above phenomenon has more direct embodiment in each big airline's management data.

January operating data show that, air China (Url: AIRYY / LSE: AIRC) , China Southern Airlines (Url) and China Eastern Airline (600115.sh/00670.HK/NYSE:CEA，下称) reported declines of 2.9% , 2.42% and 1.28% respectively.

Passenger turnover is the product of the number of passengers and the distance, which reflects both the quantity and the distance of the transportation, and can fully reflect the results of the transportation.

And the occupancy rate isn't great. Hainan Airlines Holding Co. , Ltd. (URL) , Shanghai Jixiang Airlines Co. , Ltd. (url) and Chunqiu Airlines Co. , Ltd. (601021.Sh ) reported a 9.21% , 6.84% and 7.85% year-on-year decrease in occupancy in January.

What's worse is that cash flow is tight because of the large number of flights grounded. Civil Aviation Industry has always been a high-input, high-risk industry. Many airlines have chosen to issue debt and reduce labor costs to control cash outflows.

However, these are short-term measures. Zhang Wuan, vice president of Chunqiu Airlines, told Caijing that the recovery of scheduled flights is the main way to get a large amount of cash flow.

Lanxiang, vice president of Qunar, pointed out to the reporter of Caijing that many passengers have not reduced their search for flights. As you can see, many travelers have not yet released their travel needs, which are likely to be new travelers, such as those who need to return to work or go on business trips. At least 8 million return flights are expected to be released.

Travel is just needed, flights will eventually gradually recover. The overall flight performance rate of mainland airlines on Feb. 25 was 3.78 percent higher than the previous day, according to Fiyo technology.

But will slow growth allow airlines to cope with the coming traditionally slow season? Can the airline that lacks spring transportation income still hold out to summer transportation season?

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A cash-strapped airline

Poor debt-paying, cash-strapped and financing airlines are struggling

"since the implementation of the free refund policy, so far 20 million tickets have been refunded by domestic and foreign airlines, involving a total face value of more than 20 billion yuan, " said Li Jian, deputy director of the Civil Aviation Administration of China, at a State Affairs Office press conference on Feb. 15.

Airlines are having a hard time refunding their tickets and paying their employees, while they are cutting back on flights because of a lack of passengers.

China's civil aviation industry has always been a highly indebted industry. Air China, China Southern, China Eastern, HNA, Chunqiu and Jixiang have debt ratios of 64.8 percent, 73.9 percent, 74.5 percent, 65 percent, 49.4 percent and 55.8 percent, respectively, according to the third quarter 2019 reports of all listed airlines.

With the exception of two private carriers with a fleet of about 100 aircraft, the debt ratios of the four larger carriers are all high. Air China's Shenzhen Airlines in the last three years debt ratio is about 85% of the high.

High debt alone is not fatal for airlines, and insolvency and cash flow are the most deadly.

According to the third quarter 2019 results, the bigger the airline, the less solvent it is. Air China has a flow ratio of 0.3 and a quick-moving ratio of 0.29, China Southern has a flow ratio of 0.13 and a quick-moving ratio of 0.17, China Eastern has a flow ratio of 0.26 and a quick-moving ratio of 0.22, and HNA has a flow ratio of 0.44 and a quick-moving ratio of 0.43 Auspicious air flow rate is 0.71, quick-moving rate is 0.69, Spring and autumn air flow rate is 1.14, quick-moving rate is 1.13.

Generally speaking, the liquidity ratio is 2, the quick ratio is 1, is the company solvency ideal model. The lower the number, the worse the solvency.

With the exception of Air China and HNA, China Southern, China Eastern, Spring Airlines and Lucky Airways all have accounts receivable turnover of less than 10 days, which means the airlines have to rely on cash. Since 2020, when China's new crown pneumonia broke out, Chinese airlines have not been able to reap the dividends of the Spring Festival travel rush, and cash inflows have plummeted. Some airlines have even stopped flying altogether, cutting off cash inflows.

The 40-day 2020 Spring Festival travel rush ended on February 18. In 40 days, 38.39 million passengers were sent by civil aviation, down 47.5 percent from the same period last year. As recently as December 2019, the Ministry of Transport of the People's Republic of China predicted 79 million passenger flights would be carried during the 2020 Spring Festival travel season.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Zhang said that during the entire Spring Festival travel period, the number of spring and autumn air flights decreased by about 60 per cent. Passenger traffic is less than half of what it was in 2019, with less than half as much revenue and cash flow as last year.

"there is still a lot of pressure on small and medium-sized airlines, and no one dares to say what the future holds, " a mid-level local small-sized airline told CAIJING.

Revenues are falling, expenses are not falling. Airlines still need to pay for their aircraft, equipment and office space on time. Airport parking fees are also required for non-flying aircraft. Staff salaries remain an important expense.

For some airlines, these costs can be met in the short term. At the end of the third quarter of last year, for example, Air China and Spring Airlines had cash balances of 7.6 billion yuan and 8.04 billion yuan.

Liu Haoran, pricewaterhousecoopers'chief consultant for Aviation Business Services, told CAIJING that for small airlines that used to rely on financing to cope with their daily expenses, the market is stagnant, and financial institutions have reduced or stopped lending, these companies will be at risk.

And the income source of Chinese airline is more unitary, basically rely on airline ticket income to and FRO blood. Yu Zhanfu, global partner of Management Consulting, told Caijing that some airlines have diversified their business, but also around the aviation industry, such as into aviation catering, aviation logistics. The overall recession in the airline industry, will make airlines no risk dispersion point.

Short-term debt issuance

Issuing bonds and reducing manpower cost are the dominant means for airlines to alleviate the liquidity crisis

In the event of a short-term revenue collapse, the last survivor will be the one who gets the most cash. Open source and cut cost become the current key point of airline company.

Issuing bonds has become an option for many airlines. "CAIJING" reporter statistics, since January 10,2020, six airlines and groups issued ultra-short-term financing vouchers.

China Eastern and China Eastern Group issued the largest amount. Since January 16,2020, China Eastern Airlines and China Eastern Group issued eight ultra-short-term financing vouchers, a total of 17 billion yuan. China Southern Airlines and China Southern Airlines group followed suit, issuing 12.4 billion yuan in ultra-short-term financing vouchers, eight times.

Shenzhen Airlines, which is owned by Air China, is also raising debt. Up to the end of June 2019, Shenzhen Airlines total debt 46 billion yuan, asset-liability ratio reached 86.9% , the last three years Shenzhen Airlines asset-liability ratio has been maintained at a high level of about 85% .

On January 10, Shenzhen Airlines issued its first ultra-short-term financing bonds in 2020, with an actual issuance amount of 400 million yuan and an issuance interest rate of 2% , setting a record low for AAA-rated corporate debt since 2017.

On February 11, Shenzhen Airlines issued the first 500 million yuan ultra-short-term epidemic prevention and control debt with a duration of 180 days, with an interest rate of 2% , to supplement the operating funds spent during the epidemic due to free transportation and refund of tickets.

In the first two months of 2020, Shenzhen Airlines issued 3 issues of 1.8 billion yuan in ultra-short-term epidemic prevention and control debt, in addition to 3 issues of 1.2 billion yuan in ultra-short-term financing.

Shenzhen aviation related personage tells"finance and Economics"reporter, this is a capital emergency plan, basically be to provide safeguard for epidemic prevention work, look at this job to still continue at present. Shenzhen Airlines canceled about 50 percent of its flights, and as of January 30,113 flights had been provided free of charge to transport 56 tons of epidemic prevention materials, at a total transportation cost of 20 million yuan; as of February 5, the total amount of refund for passengers is about 500 million yuan.

In addition, Sichuan Airlines and Xiamen Airlines have issued ultra-short-term financing vouchers. Spring Airlines announced plans to issue a total of no more than 5 billion yuan of epidemic debt.

Banks and local governments are also a source of cash. In early February, Spring Airlines took just three days to get a 900 million yuan loan from the industrial and Commercial Bank of China. On February 10, Spring Airlines received a total of 63.74 million yuan in support funds from the Changning District government to "cash in advance and pay for the materials later" . "CAIJING" reporter learned that from the capital to make a project, to the final determination of the program, but also only three days.

A direct alternative to financial means of maintaining cash flow in the short term is to reduce the cost of labour. This is the approach taken by the majority of Private Airlines.

CAIJING, a large airline in southern China with huge debts, has been asking its employees to take unpaid days off since January. Employees at the airline's subsidiary told Caijing that, because the company was doing well, salaries were delayed by three or four days, but not half as previously rumored.

The majority of Spring and Autumn Aviation Cadres said that voluntary in a special period do not take or less pay, and the company to tide over the difficulties. The move will no doubt help slow the company's cash outflow.

Employees are important assets of the company and should not be made redundant because of short-term difficulties, Yu said. Once the epidemic is over, the company will still need a large number of professional staff to run. For now, maintaining labor relations and reducing payroll costs is one option.

That said, airlines still shed tears over Ma Su when it comes to overpaying employees.

Hainan Airlines plans to lay off more than 100 Russian pilots and China Southern plans to lay off about 10, Tass reported. Not only will airlines cut Russian pilots, but the number of foreign pilots in general is also decreasing.

Long-term by flying more

Only the resumption of regular flights, in order to long-term blood

These measures, however well played, are temporary measures to address liquidity in the short term, and the real centrepiece for airlines should be the resumption of flights.

Xiamen Airlines staff told CAIJING that one of Xiamen Airlines' current measures to deal with the impact of the epidemic is to "keep flying more and more. ". The so-called "variable flight" is to ensure that the recovery of variable costs on the basis of increasing aircraft utilization, more flights.

There are two kinds of cost in the process of airline operation, one is fixed cost, the other is variable cost. Fixed cost is the cost that has no direct cause and effect with the change of business volume in relevant scope. For example, aircraft engine depreciation costs, aircraft engine overhaul costs, employee wages and benefits subsidies. Variable cost refers to the cost which is proportional to the change of business volume in the relevant scope. For example aviation fuel consumption, aviation material consumption, on-board food, take-off and landing fees and so on.

Lian Peikun, director of research at UBS securities, told Caijing that since aviation is a high-input, low-cash-flow industry with high fixed costs, the only way for the company to maintain cash income in the short term is to do charter flights.

On February 18, China Southern, China Eastern, Spring Airlines, Jixiang Airlines, Xiamen Airlines, Hebei Airlines, Gulf of Tonkin Airlines, Fuzhou Airlines and other major airlines launched charter sales posters. For a time in the circle of friends in the screen, dubbed as the air version of the "inter-provincial Charter" battle for passenger resources.

On the same day, Spring Airlines flew the first charter flight back to Huzhou. About 180 Yunnan workers boarded a spring and autumn air charter flight from Kunming to Shanghai, where they landed and were transferred to Huzhou by seven buses.

Zhang Wu'an revealed that the spring and Autumn Airlines charter flights mainly from the West to the east, such as Yunnan, Guizhou, Sichuan, Gansu and other major labor-exporting provinces, to the east, Zhejiang, Jiangsu and areas of labor-intensive industrial clusters. Spring and Autumn Airlines also opened Lanzhou, Chengdu to the east of the flight.

On Feb. 24, China Eastern Airlines flew from Zhengzhou to Shanghai with 160 Sebang employees on board. "It feels good to fly back to Shanghai for the first time, " Wu Wenchao, an employee of Shibang industrial technology group, told CAIJING.

Not only do employees feel good, companies and airlines love it. In the context of the gradual resumption of work in the national enterprises, it has become a major problem for enterprises how to safely return the scattered staff to work. Shibang Group Deputy General Manager Fang Libo told Caijing that the group considered trains, buses, planes and other options, and finally in the budget controllable circumstances, the choice of aircraft. Because of the speed of the aircraft transport, and the whole process is safe and controllable.

Charter costs, cubic wave revealed, than high-speed rail costs twice, more than bus transport 50%-60% . Overall transportation costs are in line with expectations, and China Eastern is offering a discount price, which is lower than the market price.

For Airlines, the resumption of charter flights is not only a good opportunity to fulfill social responsibility, but also a good measure to reduce losses.

Shen Jinjun, Vice General Manager of China Eastern Airlines'Marketing Committee, told Caijing that the minimum number of China Eastern Airlines charter flights is very low at this stage, so most of the charter flights are performed below operating costs. The first consideration of China Eastern is not the economic account, but the social responsibility account of the Central Enterprise. As of February 27, China Eastern Airlines has received nearly 100 flight charter demand.

In Zhang Wuan's view, charter business can not bring too much cash flow, cash flow mainly depends on the recovery of scheduled flights.

The civil aviation industry is gradually recovering. According to Fiyo Technology, 8,005 flights were canceled nationwide on Feb. 25, with a cancellation rate of 62.91 percent, reaching the lowest level in nearly a week. The Utilization Rate of aircraft was 2.11 hours / day, and the daily utilization rate was 1.93 percent higher than the previous day.

Airline compliance rates are also rising. On Feb. 25, the implementation rates of Sichuan Airlines, Xiamen Airlines, Air China and China Southern Airlines were 68.2 percent, 56.8 percent, 46.5 percent and 28.4 percent, respectively, up 8 percent, 0.9 percent, 2.8 percent and 2.1 percent from the previous day. The overall flight performance rate of mainland airlines on February 25 was 3.78% higher than the previous day.

Like the Spring and Autumn Airlines, Lucky Airlines, such as private airlines are playing the price card to attract customers. Chen Li, a senior at School of Medicine, Shanghai Jiao Tong University, found on Feb. 25 that the lowest fare for a flight from Shanghai to Chengdu that day was 80 yuan, carried by Chengdu Airlines.

In addition, auspicious aviation, Spring and Autumn Aviation also rolled out less than 150 yuan Shanghai fly Chengdu ticket. Chen Li told Caijing that air tickets between Shanghai and Chengdu usually cost more than 800 yuan during the off-season. "I didn't expect to get 80 yuan this year. " But that's just the price of a one-way ticket from Shanghai to Chengdu. As a hot return route, Chengdu to fly to Shanghai ticket prices are not so cheap, the price given by the airlines are more than a thousand yuan.

Civil Aviation expert Lin Zhijie told the "financial" reporter, airline fares by the airline operating guidelines, the impact of the flight occupancy rate. But no matter how fares change, airlines normally fly only if revenue from flights covers the cost of change.

Will the SARS model be repeated

Whether or not the v-shaped model will emerge again depends on overall economic growth, which is hard to see now

Flight volumes are gradually recovering, but the start of the year is still difficult, and China's civil aviation industry hopes to replicate the retaliatory rebound after the SARS epidemic in 2003.

In the second quarter of 2003, when the SARS epidemic was at its worst, China's civil aviation industry was hit hard.

In April of that year, CAAC carried 5.73 million passengers, down 25.6 percent year-on-year. In May, it carried 1.63 million passengers, down 77.9 percent year-on-year. The throughput of the main infected Guangzhou Baiyun International Airport and Beijing and Beijing Capital International Airport dropped 81.4 percent and 86.5 percent respectively.

In late June, the World Health Organization removed Beijing from its list of affected areas, and the SARS epidemic was largely under control, with passenger traffic reaching 3.15 million that month, double the number in May. In the second half of the following year, passenger traffic rose sharply, by 20.1% and 14.3% respectively.

In 2003, despite a halving of passenger traffic in the second quarter, CAAC saw positive growth in the second half of the year alone: 87.59 million passengers were transported, up 1.9 per cent year-on-year.

But in 2020, when the civil aviation industry has doubled in size, such upturns are no longer possible.

In 2003, the Civil Aviation of China (CAAC) was in the stage of high-speed development. The growth rates of passenger traffic in the previous three years were 10.3% , 11.9% and 14.2% respectively.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
After years of high-speed development, the civil aviation industry has entered a medium-speed development stage since 2019. In addition, influenced by factors such as economic and trade frictions between China and the United States and geopolitical factors, the growth rate of passenger traffic in 2019 dropped to 7.9 percent. If normal operation is maintained, growth is expected to be around 7% in 2020.

The upward trend of 17 years ago is no longer, UBS securities estimates that, assuming the epidemic ends by July this year, full-year demand in 2020 will fall 10% year-on-year.

At the same time, the epidemic situation of NCP has a greater impact on the civil aviation industry than SARS. In 2003 SARS epidemic peak appeared in the second quarter, and the second quarter has always been the civil aviation off-season, before the civil aviation has eaten the spring transportation bonus, also enjoyed the summer transportation peak after the epidemic.

In 2020, the outbreak of new pneumonia broke out earlier. After the city of Wuhan was closed on January 23, a number of provinces across the country launched a first-level response. Domestic flights were greatly reduced, and international flights were also largely grounded. Airlines not only lost the Spring Festival travel peak, the impact of the epidemic may even extend to the "May Day" holiday, hope only in July, August summer travel season.

Liu Haoran believes that the impact of the new pneumonia epidemic far beyond the SARS period. During the SARS period, only Beijing, Guangdong, Hong Kong and other parts of the region have an impact. The regional characteristics of the affected airlines are obvious. But this new crown pneumonia epidemic has affected the national and even the global aviation industry.

The International Air Transport Association (IATA)'s preliminary assessment of the impact of the new pneumonia outbreak on the air transport industry suggests that airline passenger demand in the asia-pacific region could fall by 13 per cent a year. IATA had previously forecast a 4.8 per cent increase in passenger traffic in the asia-pacific region. However, due to the impact of the epidemic, the region's annual passenger demand will fall by 8.2% year-on-year.

Based on this estimate, airlines in the asia-pacific region could lose $27.8 BILLION IN REVENUE IN 2020, most of which would come from Chinese airlines, and the loss to China's domestic passenger market could reach $12.8 billion.

Assuming that demand losses are limited to china-related markets, airlines outside the asia-pacific region would lose $1.5 billion in revenue, Global Airlines would lose an estimated $29.3 billion in revenue, and passenger demand would fall 4.7 percent.

These estimates are based on the assumption that NPV is similar to the SARS v Model. The aviation industry under the SARS epidemic was characterized by a sharp decline within six months and a rapid recovery thereafter. In 2003, SARS caused a 5.1% drop in passenger km for airlines in the asia-pacific region.

Alexandre de Juniac, IATA's co-chairman and Chief Executive, says the period has been challenging for the global air transport industry. Alexander Gazsi JUNIAC, chairman and chief executive of IATA, said:. The priority is to stop the virus from spreading. The new coronavirus will cause the first decline in total passenger demand since the onset of the global financial crisis in 2008-2009. "It's going to be a tough year for airlines. ".

Lanxiang, vice president of Qunar, said in an interview with Caijing that confidence in the tourism industry should be restored at least one month after the end of the epidemic. Although many passengers now cancel travel, but many passengers on the flight search volume has not decreased. As can be seen, many of the travel needs of passengers have not released, this part may be just need to travel passengers, need to return to work or have to travel groups. At least 8 million return flights are expected to be released.

This year will be a long winter for China's aviation industry. But there is hope in the long winter.
